Q. What is Reflection ?

Reflection is the ability of Java to examine and manipulate its own structure at runtime.

More about it:

👉 Reflection is a feature in Java that allows a program to:

(i)Inspect classes, methods, fields at runtime
(ii)Create objects dynamically
(iii)Access private members
(iv)Invoke methods dynamically

🔷 2️⃣ Why Reflection exists

Normally in Java:

User user = new User();
user.getName();

👉 Everything is known at compile time

But sometimes:

-Class name is not known beforehand
-Methods are dynamic
-Framework needs flexibility

👉 Reflection solves this

🔷 3️⃣ Core Classes in Reflection

All reflection comes from:

👉 java.lang.reflect package

🔑 Important classes:
Class	                                  Purpose
Class	                                  Represents class metadata
Method	                                  Represents method
Field	                                  Represents variable
Constructor	                              Represents constructor

🔷 4️⃣ How Reflection Works (Step-by-step)

🔹 Step 1: Get Class Object

Class<?> clazz = Class.forName("User");

OR

Class<?> clazz = User.class;

🔹 Step 2: Create Object

Object obj = clazz.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();

🔹 Step 3: Access Fields

Field field = clazz.getDeclaredField("name");
field.setAccessible(true);
field.set(obj, "Tanisha");

🔹 Step 4: Call Methods

Method method = clazz.getDeclaredMethod("getName");
String result = (String) method.invoke(obj);

🔷 5️⃣ Internal Working (Important 🔥)

When you use reflection:

👉 JVM:

(i)Loads class metadata into memory
(ii)Creates Class object
(iii)Uses metadata to:
(iv)Find fields/methods
(v)Invoke them dynamically

❗ Why reflection is slower?

Normal call:

user.getName();

Reflection call:

method.invoke(user);

👉 Extra steps:

-Lookup method
-Security checks
-Dynamic invocation

🔷 6️⃣ Breaking Encapsulation (Important)
field.setAccessible(true);

👉 Allows access to:

(i)private
(ii)protected

⚠️ This is powerful but dangerous

🔷 7️⃣ Real-world Use Cases of Reflection

✅ 1. Frameworks (Most important)

Frameworks like:
-Spring Framework
-Hibernate

👉 Use reflection heavily

✅ 2. Dependency Injection:

(i)Creating objects dynamically
(ii)Injecting dependencies

✅ 3. Annotation Processing
if (clazz.isAnnotationPresent(Entity.class))

👉 Used in:
-Spring
-Hibernate

✅ 4. Testing Frameworks
JUnit

👉 Finds methods with @Test and runs them

✅ 5. Serialization/Deserialization
JSON libraries (like Jackson)
Map JSON ↔ Object

✅ 6. Dynamic Proxies
Used in AOP (logging, transactions)

🔷 8️⃣ Reflection in Spring Boot (VERY IMPORTANT 🔥)

Spring Boot (built on Spring Framework) uses reflection everywhere.

🔥 1. Bean Creation:

@Service
class UserService {}

👉 Spring:

(i)   Scans classpath
(ii)  Finds annotation
(iii) Creates object using reflection

🔥 2. Dependency Injection
@Autowired
private UserService userService;

👉 Internally:

field.setAccessible(true);
field.set(obj, dependency);

🔥 3. Controller Method Execution

@GetMapping("/hello")
public String hello() { return "Hi"; }

👉 When request comes:

Spring finds method
Calls:
method.invoke(controller);

🔥 4. Reading Annotations
if (clazz.isAnnotationPresent(Service.class))

👉 Used in:

-Component scanning
-Configuration

🔥 5. Spring Data JPA
interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {}

👉 You don’t implement anything 😲

👉 Spring:

Generates implementation using reflection + proxies

🔥 6. AOP (Transactions, Logging)

@Transactional

👉 Spring:

-Creates proxy
-Intercepts method
-Uses reflection to invoke actual method

🔷 9️⃣ Advantages of Reflection

✔ Very flexible
✔ Enables frameworks
✔ Reduces boilerplate
✔ Dynamic behavior

🔷 🔟 Disadvantages

❌ Slower than normal calls
❌ Breaks encapsulation
❌ Hard to debug
❌ Security risks

🔷 1️⃣1️⃣ Modern Optimization (Important)

👉 Newer Java + Spring:

Reduce reflection using:
-AOT (Ahead-of-Time compilation)
-Bytecode generation

🔷 1️⃣2️⃣ Real-life Analogy

Without reflection:

You know exactly who to call

With reflection:

You look at a directory and dynamically find & call people

🔷 🔥 Final Interview Answer:

Reflection in Java allows inspection and manipulation of classes, methods, and fields at runtime.
It is widely used in frameworks like Spring Boot for creating beans, injecting dependencies,
invoking methods, and processing annotations. While powerful and flexible, it has performance
overhead and should be used carefully.